ars = 40 - rank. To get 25+ free vars, rank would need to be ≤15 with 40 equations. That means at most 15 of 40 equations are independent — possible if buttons affect overlapping sets of lights in a very structured way.\n\nLet me improve the approach for robustness. For GF(2), I'll implement a proper weight-enumeration approach when free variables exceed a threshold.\n\nLet me also reconsider the GF(p) greedy approach. The coordinate-descent optimization I have is not guaranteed to find the global optimum. Let me think about what the constraint says: \"Must handle up to 40 buttons, 40 counters, and modulus up to 97. Must complete in under 5 seconds.\" With 40 buttons and 40 counters, the system should have at most 40 free variables in the worst case (rank 0), but 97^40 is astronomical. However, with a prime modulus system of 40 equations in 40 unknowns, the rank should typically be 40, meaning 0 free variables.\n\nLet me refine my implementation to handle edge cases better."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":395,"cache_read_input_tokens":31726,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":395},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"620c06da-2803-48ca-a38a-474bcd86aa03","uuid":"3291b156-1424-4595-9601-17eaee118de8"}
