r the meet-in-the-middle approach to minimize Hamming weight:\n- Split the numButtons variables into two halves (not the free variables)\n- For each first-half free variable assignment, compute the values of the first-half variables\n- For each second-half free variable assignment, compute the values of the second-half variables\n- The total weight is the sum of weights of both halves\n\nBut the two halves are coupled through the nullspace vectors. Each nullspace vector affects variables in both halves.\n\nA cleaner approach: for each first-half free variable assignment, compute the full solution and extract just the first-half weight. Store these, sorted by first-half weight. Then for each second-half free variable assignment, compute the second-half weight of the full solution (using the full solution from the corresponding first-half assignment XOR the second-half nullspace contribution).\n\nThis is still O(2^(n/2) * 2^(n/2)) in the worst case.\n\nOK, let me just accept that for extremely large free variable counts (>20 in GF(2)), I'll use a greedy approach instead. In practice, with 40 buttons and 40 lights, the system will almost certainly have rank close to min(40,40), giving very few free variables. Let me replace the meet-in-the-middle with a greedy approach for numFree > 20:"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":272,"cache_read_input_tokens":59045,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":272},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"620c06da-2803-48ca-a38a-474bcd86aa03","uuid":"f77a64e3-f0ec-4cf6-b574-c2e9ad935115"}
